❌Common Push-Up Mistakes and How to Fix It!

1️⃣Flared out elbows or what I like to call “Chicken-Wings.
By flaring out your elbows, it causes extra strain in your shoulder, which leads to not being able to engage your lats. So instead of this, think of creating a triangle with the space between your body and your arms; think 45 degrees vs 90 degree.

2️⃣Keeping fingers too close together.
Spread those fingers and open up those palms. By doing so, you are creating a bigger base for yourself to not only grip the floor but also to keep you stable as you move your bodyweight towards the floor.

➡️So, next time you have push-ups as part of your workout, try these out and see how you feel afterwards!

If you are looking to level up your RDLs, try these 2 variations:

1. Staggered Single Dumbbell RDLs - Keep your heels up: you can find more stability with this variation where you can generally lift more weights compared to a Single Leg variation while still targeting hamstrings, glutes, core, lats and forearms. 
2. Kickstand Single DB RDLs - Keep your heels down: similar to a staggered stance, this allows the back foot to provide stability, while targeting the front leg. 

With both variation, you are training the body to prepare for a more advanced skill. You will also be able to work up to more weight being used with less worry of losing balance. Adding variety to certain movement is another way we can add progressive overload to our training.

Give these 2 variations a try and let me know what you think!

3 Things I’m Keeping from 2022.

I practiced these 3 things last year and will continue to keep practicing them this year and for years to come and here’s why:

1. Rest/Recovery Days - it took me years to really implement this but it is now a regular part of my weekly routine. Taking rest days doesn’t mean you’re weak or lazy, it means that you value your body to honor what it needs. Rest days are for letting your body recover, letting your muscles repair and removing a stressor to your body. Rest days are just as important as your workouts.

2. Strength Over Aesthetics - it took me being pregnant and postpartum to fully embrace this. Body image is such a confusing subject and we often think that looking a certain way makes us who we are. But it’s quite the opposite. Chasing the leanest version of yourself all year round is not sustainable so chase being strong and healthy instead.

3. Less is More - I say this in regards to almost every aspect of life. More doesn’t mean better, oftentimes it complicates things. So keep things simple: eating whole foods, moving your body, taking walks, quality sleep and everything else will follow. It’s as simple as that.

What did 2022 teach you?

Long-term consistency beats short-term intensity.

As humans, we automatically think the quicker it is, the better it will be. While that might be the case in some aspects of life, not all roads lead to success when you’re wanting instant gratification.

Realizing that it takes steps, one by one to create a result–can help you stay focused on the journey.

You are not going to instantly lose inches, you’re not going to instantly have defined arms, just like you’re not going to instantly know how to ride a bike the first time you sit on one. It took time and consistency.

Remain consistent. Creating balance in your life is what will keep you grounded and efficient.

Becoming intense and hurried can never ensure the best results. Rushing into a fad diet, or exercising off 2022 is not a good or healthy way to approach a healthier you.

Stay the course. You may trip or fall from time to time, but what matters is you get right back up and keep peddling your way to your goals.

Are your goals aligned with your nutrition?
Do you workout 4-6x/week and haven’t seen much change in your body?

If you’re not seeing the muscle gains you want with how much you workout, it’s possible that you’re not eating enough to support muscle growth.

Eating at a maintenance or even at a caloric surplus provides your body with the energy it needs to build new muscle tissue.

Building new muscle tissue requires energy and nutrients. If you’re not eating enough, your body won’t have the necessary resources to build new muscle tissue. When you give your body more food, you provide your body with the extra energy it needs to fuel muscle protein synthesis.

In addition to energy, your body also needs specific nutrients to build muscle tissue. Protein is particularly important for muscle growth, as it provides the building blocks (amino acids) your body needs to repair and build muscle tissue. This is why we prioritize protein.

So, make sure you’re eating enough to support your goals, and focus on consuming nutrient-dense foods to maximize your gains!

Align your goals with nutrition and see the potential of your body!

3 Important Reminders During your Weight-Loss Journey:

1. Your weight will fluctuate DAILY.
This is a fact. It doesn’t mean you *gained* fat. It means your body is going through its daily process:
-digestion
-stress
-time of the month
-workouts
-food has weight, you eat food, your weight will go up
-sleep
-poop
-sweat
… must I go on? 🤪

2. Carbs are not the ENEMY.
In fact, they can actually help you reach your goals. Carbohydrates are a vital source of energy for your body, and cutting them out completely can leave you feeling tired and sluggish. Plus, many high-carb foods like fruits, veggies, and whole grains are packed with micronutrients that your body needs to function at its best.

3. WALKING can be a powerful (underrated) tool.
It’s free, low-impact, and accessible to almost everyone. Not to mention, it’s a great way to get some fresh air and clear your mind. Plus, research has shown that walking can be just as effective as more intense forms of exercise for weight loss and overall health.

NEAT (Non-Exercise Activity Thermogenesis), which is all the energy you burn during daily activities like walking, fidgeting, standing, basicaly by existing. By adding more walking to your day, you can increase your NEAT and in turn, increase your total daily energy expenditure (TDEE). This means that you’ll burn more calories throughout the day, even when you’re not working out.

So next time you are questioning yourself… remember these 3 reminders and JUST.KEEP.GOING!

Do you ever find yourself saying the words “I can’t ___ because___”?

What do I mean by this?

Becoming aware of the story you tell yourself can drastically change how you view your circumstances.

The “I Can’t” vs “I Don’t” mentality, and how it can drastically shift how you think. 

Any time you catch yourself saying the words “I can’t...”, pause. Take the opportunity to self-assess. 
 
Are you ready/willing to do the thing you are saying you can’t do? 
Are you taking responsibility for your actions? 
Do you truly believe you can’t?

What happens if you turn your “I can’t” into “I don’t”? How does that sit with you? Here are some common examples:
 
“I can’t meal prep because... XYZ.” 
BECOMES
“I DON’T meal prep because... XYZ”
 
- or -
 
“I can’t go to the gym because... XYZ”
BECOMES
“I don’t go to the gym because... XYZ”
 
Oooo, can you smell that personal responsibility coming off of those “I don’t” statements? Yikes. I found that it’s much easier to lie to yourself when it’s an “I can’t” statement. 
 
As soon as you take personal responsibility by saying “I don’t” you take control of your circumstance, and begin to question whether or not that thing you thought you couldn’t do is really something you weren’t WILLING to do. 
 
Perhaps you now realize that it’s more of a CHOICE you are making.

You CAN do whatever you think you CAN, it’s up to you to make that CHOICE.

Next time you catch yourself slacking, try this out and shift your mindset.

#mindsetshift #takeresponsibility #yesyoucan #macrocoach

Spot the difference!

The lunge is a popular lower body exercise that targets multiple muscles. The main difference between the 2 lunge movements is the positioning of the torso. By adjusting the position of your torso during a lunge, you can emphasize either the glutes or the quads, altering the focus of the movement. Incorporating a mix of these lunge variations into your lower body workouts can help you target different muscle groups and achieve a well-rounded leg workout.

Video on the left: Quads
To target the quads more during the lunge, you’ll want to focus on maintaining an upright torso. Avoid leaning forward as you lunge down. This places more emphasis on the front leg and increases the activation of the glutes. Make sure to keep your chest lifted and engage your core to maintain stability.

Video on the right: Glutes
If you want to target the glutes more, you can lean slightly forward during the lunge. As you step forward into the lunge, allow your torso to lean forward over the front leg. Be sure to keep your back straight and avoid rounding your shoulders.

🚫 Nutrient Deprivation: With limited calories, it’s nearly impossible to meet our nutritional needs, leading to deficiencies and health complications. Severely restricting calories can lead to inadequate intake of essential nutrients, leaving our bodies deprived of vital vitamins and minerals.

🚫 Muscle Loss: Inadequate calories may cause the body to break down muscle tissue, sabotaging fitness goals and overall strength.

🚫 Mental & Emotional Toll: Extreme dieting can lead to stress, anxiety, and an unhealthy relationship with food, affecting both physical and mental well-being.

🚫 Energy Drain: Our bodies need fuel to function optimally. Insufficient calories can zap energy levels, leaving us feeling tired and fatigued. Not to mention it down regulates thyroid function and hormone health.

🚫 Individual Differences Ignored: Each person has unique dietary requirements based on age, gender, activity level, and metabolism. A one-size-fits-all approach can be harmful.

❌Your cardio machine is lying to you!

Most of you may already know this but for those that still believe the “calories burned” numbers from your cardio machine, this post is for you.

1. Calories Burned are Estimated: The calorie count displayed on cardio machines is just an estimate based on general formulas. It doesn’t consider your individual metabolism, body composition, or fitness level, making it highly inaccurate for gauging your true energy expenditure.

2. Intensity and Duration: The calorie count displayed on cardio machines often doesn’t consider the impact of the individual’s rate of exertion and duration to accurately spit out numbers.

3. The Afterburn: While cardio workouts do burn calories during the exercise itself, they also have a positive impact on your metabolism after you’re done. This is known as the “afterburn” effect or excess post-exercise oxygen consumption (EPOC), where your body continues to burn calories as it recovers. The calorie count displayed on the machine doesn’t take this afterburn into account.

Share this with that one friend who still believes the cardio machine.😉

RMR- Resting Metabolic Rate: What is it, how to increase and why its important in your fitness journey.

RMR is the amount of energy your body requires to maintain basic physiological functions while at rest. Think breathing, circulating blood, regulating body temperature, and supporting cellular processes that are essential for life.

Increasing your RMR means burning more calories at rest which is a factor we consider when you’re trying to lose or maintain your weight.

So how do you increase RMR?

By increasing muscle mass! More muscle means increased metabolism.

1️⃣ Muscle tissue is metabolically active, which means it requires more energy to maintain than fat. The more muscle you have, the higher your RMR.
2️⃣ Building muscle through resistance training helps you burn calories during your workout AND long after, thanks to the “afterburn” effect.

And extra bonus: muscles provides better support for your bones and joints, improving overall physical health and injury prevention.

But I also want to note that building muscle takes time + also proper nutrition. So while it sounds easy, remember that this can take months and years and the willingness to change!

And I am never going back to this mentality ⬇️

I used to eat based on how many calories I burned in my workout that day.

Why is this the wrong mentality when it comes to food?

Because our BMR (or RMR) matters, as well as our TDEE.

1️⃣ Our Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) Matters: BMR represents the calories your body needs to perform its basic functions, like breathing and cell repair. It’s always working, whether you’re hitting the gym or chilling on the couch. Ignoring this vital aspect means depriving your body of essential energy.

2️⃣ Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE) is Unique: TDEE factors in your daily activity level, not just your workouts. It varies from person to person, and it’s influenced by age, gender, muscle mass, and more. To optimize nutrition, consider your TDEE rather than just the calories burned during exercise.

3️⃣ Quality Over Quantity: What you eat is as crucial as how much you eat. Focusing solely on calorie expenditure (calories out) often leads to poor food choices. Prioritize nutrient-dense foods that fuel your body for everyday activities and help you recover from workouts.

Also, PS: your Apple Watch or whatever wearable gadget you have is lying to you anyways. 😉

I still can’t believe it’s Thanksgiving next week 🤯

The holiday season is a time of joy, celebration, and togetherness and it also means shared moment around food. BUT it can also be a challenging period for maintaining a healthy balance between indulging in festive treats and taking care of your well-being.

So before the holiday festivities begin, ask yourself these questions:

1️⃣Am I Intuned with My Hunger Cues?
Take a moment to connect with your body. Are you truly hungry, or are you eating out of habit or social pressure? 

2️⃣What Does Moderation Mean to Me?
Understand that enjoying holiday treats is part of the celebration. Establishing your limits can help you savor the flavors without overindulging.

3️⃣What Role Does Self-Compassion Play in My Celebration?
Instead of focusing on strict rules or feeling guilty about indulging, embrace self-compassion. Understand that it’s okay to enjoy festive foods and that one meal doesn’t define your overall health. 

4️⃣How Can I Prioritize Mindful Eating?
Do the by savoring each bite and appreciating the flavors and textures of your food. Allow yourself to be fully present and enjoy the moment without distractions.

5️⃣Am I Balancing Indulgences with Nutrient-Rich Choices?
While savoring holiday treats, ensure you’re also incorporating nutrient-rich foods into your meals. It’s ok to have the pie, but start with enjoying a some turkey and greens first.

6️⃣How Can I Incorporate Physical Activity Into My Celebration?
Plan activities that involve movement, such as family walks, holiday-themed games or festive dance sessions.

7️⃣What Traditions Bring Me Joy Beyond Food?
Identify and prioritize non-food-related traditions that bring you joy during the holidays. This could be decorating the house, playing games, holiday crafts, etc.

8️⃣Can I Let Go of Perfection?
Understand that holiday celebrations don’t need to be perfect. Embrace imperfections, whether they’re in your meal choices or the overall festivities. Release the pressure to conform to unrealistic expectations, allowing yourself to enjoy the season authentically.

Can you spot the difference?

The weight on the scale may be up this morning but you actually didn’t gain weight.

I did these photos to show you just that. Here are 2 big reasons why you may see a higher number today, a day after a big holiday like Thanksgiving:

1️⃣ Water Retention - larger meals, higher in carbs and sodium can lead to temporary water retention + alcohol consumption.

2️⃣ Food has Weight - more food volume and the digestive process which requires energy can add temporary weight.

If seeing this number on the scale increase gives you any negative feelings, then stay off of it for a few days.

Go back to your usual routine and accept that daily fluctuations happen! It’s your body doing what it needs to do.

Instead, be thankful that your body has allowed you to do the things that you love, especially being able to spend the holidays with your friends and family.
